title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.5: EMEGENCY PREPAREDNESS & RESPONSE - REDUCED MORTALITY AND STUNTING

description.narrative: Output 1.5 Government and non-governmental partners adopt risk-informed approaches to emergency preparedness, planning and response to humanitarian needs for Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH), nutrition, health and HIV/AIDS services., which contributes to Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Hiv Prevention, Hiv Prevention (Covid), Immunization, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition (Covid), Sanitation, Sanitation (Covid), Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv (Covid), Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition (Covid), Water, Water (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 1 - Reduced Mortality & Stunting: Increased proportions of vulnerable children, pregnant and lactating women, including adolescent girls, have equitable access to and use quality Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH), Nutrition, Health and HIV/AIDS services to reduce their risk of mortality, preventable diseases, stunting and other forms of malnutrition, and improve their birth outcomes.

title.narrative: Output 1.5 Government and non-governmental partners adopt risk-informed approaches to emergency preparedness, planning and response to humanitarian needs for WASH, nutrition, health and HIV/AIDS services.

description.narrative: UNICEF effectively responded to the humanitarian needs of over 900,000 people (600,000 children) through strengthening government-led sectoral and multi-sectoral coordination mechanisms by actively participating in the Kenya Humanitarian Partnership Team (KHPT) and the OCHA-led inter-sector working group and as well as providing critical leadership and technical support to sectoral coordination. UNICEF enhanced internal coordination and strategic guidance for effective response through eight Emergency Management Team (EMT) and Emergency Focal Point (EFP) meetings. UNICEF technical and financial support contributed to treatment of 87,622 severely malnourished children (51.2% girls) children (6-59 months) with SAM for the period January to December 2019. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/12/2019
